<div class="section">12-hour operational summary &#8212; 23 Mar 18:00 to 24 Mar 09:00 UTC+2</div>
<div class="card">
  <ul class="exec48">
    <li>
      <div class="exec-cat">
        <span class="exec-cat-title">Attack waves (12hrs)</span>
        <span class="exec-cat-val green">Declining tempo</span>
        <span class="exec-sub">Attacks continuing &middot; tempo lower than weekend peak</span>
      </div>
      <div class="exec-body">
        <b>Iran (overnight 23&#8211;24 Mar):</b> Iranian missile and drone attacks on Israel and Gulf states continued overnight but at a lower tempo than the weekend escalation, consistent with the diplomatic track opening. Sirens activated in northern Israel overnight. Missile fragments reported in West Bank (Pedu'el settlement) on 23 Mar. Iran continued 70th wave barrages against Gulf states. Britain sent short-range air defence systems to the Middle East to counter Iranian missile attacks (Starmer confirmed). Kuwait filed official protest with ICAO over Iranian "airspace violations and attacks on airport facilities."<br>
        <b>Hezbollah (overnight 23&#8211;24 Mar):</b> Rocket attacks on northern Israel continued. Kiryat Shmona bus shrapnel strike (1 severely wounded) confirmed as part of joint Iran+Hezbollah barrage 23 Mar. IDF struck Qasmiyeh Bridge in southern Lebanon overnight &#8212; IDF stated Hezbollah was using it for logistics. 1,039 people killed in Lebanon since Israel&#x27;s expanded offensive began 2 Mar per Lebanon Health Ministry (2,876 wounded; 10 deaths and 90 injuries in the past 24hrs).<br>
        <span class="trend tr-down">&#8595; TEMPO EASING</span> Attack frequency has declined since the Saturday night Dimona/Arad peak. Diplomatic track is now dominant. Both sides attacking and talking simultaneously. IDF intercepted 92% of 400+ Iranian ballistic missiles to date.
      </div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <div class="exec-cat">
        <span class="exec-cat-title">Casualties (Israel, 12hrs)</span>
        <span class="exec-cat-val green">No new fatalities</span>
        <span class="exec-sub">Period total: 19 civilians &middot; 4,697+ wounded</span>
      </div>
      <div class="exec-body">
        <b>Overnight 23&#8211;24 Mar:</b> No new Israeli fatalities confirmed. Shrapnel incidents across northern and central Israel continuing. <b>1 person severely wounded in Kiryat Shmona bus shrapnel strike</b> (joint barrage, 23 Mar afternoon &#8212; carried forward from last 12hrs). Missile debris struck West Bank settlement of Pedu&#x27;el on 23 Mar &#8212; confirmed by Flash90 photo (children photographed near crater).<br>
        <b>Period total confirmed:</b> 19 Israeli civilian deaths (incl. Moskovitz &#8212; IDF friendly fire confirmed) + 2 soldiers = 21 total. 4,697+ wounded (Jerusalem Post tracker).<br>
        <b>Lebanon context (Al Jazeera 24 Mar):</b> 1,039 killed in Lebanon since Israeli expanded offensive began 2 Mar (2,876 wounded). Iran health ministry: 1,500+ killed and 18,551 injured in Iran since 28 Feb.<br>
        <span class="trend tr-down">&#8595; IMPROVING</span> No Israeli fatalities in the 36hrs since Moskovitz (22 Mar). First extended no-fatality period since the weekend escalation. Trump 5-day energy pause and diplomatic track appear to be reducing Iranian high-intensity barrage tempo.
      </div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <div class="exec-cat">
        <span class="exec-cat-title">Diplomatic breakthrough</span>
        <span class="exec-cat-val green">Netanyahu flies to Washington</span>
        <span class="exec-sub">State Dept summit 24&#8211;25 Mar &middot; Witkoff + Araghchi + Turkey</span>
      </div>
      <div class="exec-body">
        <b>Netanyahu in Washington (24&#8211;25 Mar &#8212; KEY DEVELOPMENT):</b> Netanyahu flew to Washington for a summit at the US State Department starting 24 Mar, ending at the White House on 25 Mar. Netanyahu in a video statement: <i>"President Trump believes there is an opportunity to leverage the tremendous achievements we have reached alongside the US military to realize the goals of the war through an agreement that will safeguard our vital interests."</i> Israel will "protect our vital interests in every situation."<br>
        <b>Multi-party talks underway:</b> Meetings brought together Turkey&#x27;s FM Fidan, Iran&#x27;s Araghchi, and US special envoy Steve Witkoff, alongside parallel discussions between Ankara, Riyadh, Doha, Oman, Pakistan, and Egypt. Officials say the goal is to determine whether any path remains for de-escalation, a ceasefire, and eventually a broader political settlement. Regional diplomats warned: <b>"This may be the final opportunity to halt the war&#x27;s momentum."</b><br>
        <b>Iran&#x27;s position:</b> Iran denied any negotiations took place in the past 24 days. State media: "We have not had any talks with the US." Foreign Minister Araghchi has met with Witkoff via Turkey. Iran has not officially confirmed participation in talks.<br>
        <b>Trump on Israel:</b> "I think Israel will be very happy with what we have&#x2026; This will be peace for Israel." Trump confirmed Iran "called" to start talks &#8212; "they want to make a deal." Key goal remains no nuclear weapons for Iran.<br>
        <span class="trend tr-new">&#9888; CRITICAL SIGNAL</span> Netanyahu-Trump face-to-face in Washington with State Dept + White House summit is the highest-level diplomatic engagement since the war began. Analyst warning: if US and Iran fail to reach a deal by Friday (28 Mar, end of 5-day pause), region could see a significant spike in hostilities. Israel flagged as "most unpredictable actor" and potential spoiler.
      </div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <div class="exec-cat">
        <span class="exec-cat-title">Airspace &amp; airlines</span>
        <span class="exec-cat-val amber">Lufthansa extends to Oct</span>
        <span class="exec-sub">Dubai/TLV to 31 May &middot; other cities to 24 Oct</span>
      </div>
      <div class="exec-body">
        <b>Lufthansa (23 Mar &#8212; NEW):</b> Lufthansa extended Middle East suspension significantly. <b>Dubai and Tel Aviv: suspended to 31 May 2026.</b> Abu Dhabi, Beirut, Tehran: suspended to <b>24 October 2026.</b> Longest single suspension by any major European carrier to date. Bloomberg confirmed (Bloomberg via Times of Israel 23 Mar).<br>
        <b>Iraq airspace:</b> Extended closure additional 72hrs from Sun noon &#8212; closed to all incoming/outgoing/transit until at least Wednesday 25 Mar.<br>
        <b>Kuwait ICAO protest:</b> Kuwait&#x27;s civil aviation authority filed official protest with ICAO over Iranian "airspace violations and attacks on airport facilities" &#8212; calling them "a blatant breach of international civil aviation conventions" exposing passengers, airlines and airport personnel to serious risk.<br>
        <b>Operating:</b> El Al (~20% schedule), Arkia, Air Haifa. Israir cancelled all flights to 31 Mar. EASA CZIB renewal still pending. Ben Gurion Airport operating under PPR.<br>
        <b>Other suspensions:</b> American Airlines to 23 Apr+ &middot; Wizz Air to 7 Apr &middot; BA to 1 Jun &middot; United to 15 Jun+ &middot; EasyJet to October &middot; Air France earliest 26 Mar &middot; Delta &#8212; no date.<br>
        <span class="trend tr-up">&#8679; EXTENDED</span> Lufthansa&#x27;s October extension for Abu Dhabi/Beirut/Tehran is the first carrier to explicitly plan for a conflict duration beyond summer. Signals airline industry now pricing in a potential months-long disruption even if Israel ceasefire reached.
      </div>
    </li>
